oficiency test of L2 Norwegian by learners representing 10 different first language (L1) backgrounds. The participants of the study are immigrants to Norway and the book deals with the varying levels and types of language difficulties faced by such learners from differing backgrounds. The studies examine the learners’ use of Norwegian in relation to the morphological, syntactic, lexical, semantic and pragmatic patterns they produce in their essays. Nearly all the studies in the book rely on analytical methods specifically designed to isolate the effects of the learners’ L1s on their use of L2 Norwegian, and every chapter highlights patterns that distinguish different L1 groups from one another.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aInterlanguage (Language learning). 0aMultilingualismzNorway. 0aNorwegian languagexGrammar, Generative. 0aNorwegian languagexStudy and teachingxForeign speakers. 0aNorwegian language--Study and teaching,--Foreign speakers. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Psycholinguistics.2bisacsh  aCLI.  aL2 Norwegian.  aL2 acquisition.  aSLA.  aSecond Language Acquisition.  acrosslinguistic influence.  aimmigrants to Norway.  alearner corpora.  alearner corpus analysis.  alearner corpus.  alearners of Norwegian.  apatterns of language learning.  atransfer.1 aGolden, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolden, Anne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGujord, Ann-Kristin Helland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanik, Marta Olga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJarvis, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJarvis, Scott, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKinn, T